reviews.review_text: AS GOOD AS CORNELL THIS SHOW WITHOUT A DOUBT WOULD GIVE BARTON HALL A RUN FOR THE MONEY.AS WELL AS,COLGATE,PEMBROKE PINES,SENECA COLLEGE,ROCHESTER,HOLFEINZ PAVILLION,MOODY COLISEUM BOTTOM LINE IS BARTON HALL IS GREAT BUT FOR SURE IS NOT THE BEST.
DP 19 you'd have to be made entirely out of stone to not get chills from this Loser...best version ever!!!
nice going UJB, The Wheel and the Playin' reprise are as high level as anything from May.

@boogiesessions This show is one of my personal favourites. There is a splice in playing as is mentioned, but thankfully it is from the same show (I checked other versions of the show that I have). There is a splice in Sugaree as well here but it is not a major glitch. This also sounds brighter in some ways, but has a bit of an added hiss. In a lot of ways, the Bertha/Jay Ashley version is better. It is a little low on the treble and sounds much fuller in midrange. Except for a reel change in LLR which sort of kills the flow. DP #29 is the best version out there :)
get it! as good as anything in this month.

GHD reviews peggy o  This is the best version of Peggy O I have ever heard. Bobby kills those early licks and accompanies Jerry perfectly in every way. Jerry's solo is maybe the best solo I have ever heard. It's visceral and heartfelt with perfect build and body. Truly a masterpiece of a song.

The Fox Theater I grew up in Atlanta, GA and had the privilege of seeing many shows at Fox Theater. Unfortunately, I didn't get to see the Dead play there. The venue only holds about 2500 and my stupid brother was lucky enough to see his first Dead show there in October '85. The latter of the 2 shows played there. He enjoyed so much he drove to Columbia, SC to see the Halloween show where they opened with "Werewolves of London". I didn't get to see my first Dead show until 1987 at the Omni. But went on to see about 70 more before we lost Jerry. People rate these shows from 1☆ to 5☆. My opinion is any show that Jerry Garcia was playing was 5☆ show or more. Not just because of his talent but for his love of improvising and NOT playing things the same way twice. Although I did become very fond of his coda on "GDRFB"and when I heard a version that didn't include it was a bit disappointed. BUT I CAN TRULY SAY I AM TRULY ENVIOUS OF ANYONE & EVERYONE THAT GOT TO SEE THE GRATEFUL DEAD PLAY AT THE FOX THEATRE. IT WAS PROBABLY THE GRANDEST PLACE FOR A CONCERT THAT I HAVE EVER BEEN.
